<script>
const EXPLAINERS = {
  renters:{tag:'tag-h',tagLabel:'Housing',title:"Renters' Rights Bill: what changes for you",updated:'Updated April 2026',badges:['Private renters','England only'],
    keyFacts:["No-fault (Section 21) evictions are now illegal","Rent can only be raised once a year","You can challenge unfair rent increases at a tribunal — free","Landlords must use a court process to evict — no more just handing you a letter"],
    content:`<p>The Renters' Rights Bill is one of the biggest changes to housing law in decades. If you rent your home privately in England, this directly affects you.</p>
    <div class="highlight"><p><strong>The key change:</strong> no-fault evictions — where your landlord could ask you to leave with no reason given — are now illegal. This is the abolition of "Section 21."</p></div>
    <p>Before this law, landlords could issue a Section 21 notice and you had to leave within two months with no explanation. That power is now gone.</p>
    <p><strong>What can landlords still do?</strong> Evict you if you don't pay rent, cause serious damage, or breach your tenancy terms. These are "Section 8" grounds and require a court process.</p>
    <p><strong>What about rent increases?</strong> Landlords can only raise rent once a year and must give proper written notice. You can challenge unreasonable increases at a First-tier Tribunal — free of charge.</p>
    <p><strong>Does this apply to me?</strong> Almost all private renters in England. Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland have separate housing laws.</p>`},
  uc:{tag:'tag-b',tagLabel:'Benefits',title:'Universal Credit cuts explained',updated:'Updated April 2026',badges:['Benefits claimants','England, Wales & Scotland'],
    keyFacts:["The health element (LCWRA) is being cut for new claimants from April 2026","Existing claimants should be protected — but verify with the DWP","The Work Capability Assessment is being reformed","Citizens Advice offers free, confidential benefits support"],
    content:`<p>Changes to Universal Credit announced in 2025 will affect millions of people. Here's what's changing and what you can do.</p>
    <div class="highlight"><p><strong>The main change:</strong> the health-related element of Universal Credit (LCWRA) is being reduced for new claimants from April 2026. If you're already claiming, your award should be protected for now.</p></div>
    <p>The Work Capability Assessment — the test determining whether your health condition limits your ability to work — is also being reformed. Disability charities have raised serious concerns about the impact on vulnerable people.</p>
    <p><strong>What should I do?</strong> If you're claiming and worried, contact Citizens Advice at <a href="https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">citizensadvice.org.uk</a> for free guidance. You can also write to your MP using our letter tool.</p>`},
  voterid:{tag:'tag-v',tagLabel:'Voting',title:'Voter ID: get free photo ID in 5 minutes',updated:'Updated April 2026',badges:['All voters','England, Wales & Scotland'],
    keyFacts:["You need photo ID to vote in person at UK elections","A free Voter Authority Certificate is available from your local council","Postal voters do not need photo ID","Apply at gov.uk — takes about 5 minutes"],
    content:`<p>Since 2023, you need to show photo ID to vote in person at UK elections. Many people don't know a free document exists specifically for this purpose.</p>
    <div class="highlight"><p><strong>The free option:</strong> a Voter Authority Certificate is free photo ID issued by your local council — designed specifically for voting. Apply at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/apply-for-photo-id-voter-authority-certificate" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gov.uk</a>.</p></div>
    <p><strong>What ID is accepted?</strong> UK passport, driving licence, Blue Badge, Oyster 60+ photocard, and others. Full list at <a href="https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/voter/voter-id/accepted-forms-photo-id" target="_blank" rel="noopener">electoralcommission.org.uk</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>What about postal voting?</strong> Postal voters don't need photo ID at all. Apply for a postal vote through your local council if getting to the polling station is difficult.</p>`},
  nhs:{tag:'tag-n',tagLabel:'NHS',title:'NHS waiting lists: know your legal rights',updated:'Updated April 2026',badges:['All patients','England'],
    keyFacts:["You have a legal right to treatment within 18 weeks of GP referral","You can request treatment at a different NHS hospital","PALS (Patient Advice & Liaison) can escalate your case for free","Check waiting times for different hospitals at nhs.uk"],
    content:`<p>NHS waiting times are at record levels — but most people don't know they have legal rights and practical options.</p>
    <div class="highlight"><p><strong>Your key right:</strong> in England, you have a legal right to start consultant-led NHS treatment within 18 weeks of your GP referral. If this isn't happening, you can request to be treated elsewhere.</p></div>
    <p><strong>What can I do if I've waited too long?</strong> Contact your GP first. If that doesn't move things, ask to speak to the Patient Advice and Liaison Service (PALS) at your hospital — they can escalate your case at no cost to you.</p>
    <p><strong>Can I switch hospitals?</strong> Yes — this is called "patient choice" and it's your right. Ask your GP to refer you to an NHS provider with a shorter wait. Check times at <a href="https://www.nhs.uk/nhs-services/hospitals/guide-to-nhs-waiting-times-in-england/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nhs.uk</a>.</p>`}
};

